In article <8JUL199310575172@robot.nuceng.ufl.edu> sysop@robot.nuceng.ufl.edu (Shawn A. Clifford) writes:

>In article <TSOS.496.742113811@uni-duesseldorf.de>, you write...
>
>[...stuff omitted...]
 [... even more so ...]
>>I'd apply a hash algorithm (SHA might be fine if it spares you any 
>>licencing problems) to a concatenation of a secret string and the data. 
>>Transmit only the data, of course, plus the result from the hash 
>>algorithm. The receiver does the same calculation: Start the hash 
>>algorithm on the same secret string, then continue with the data, and 
>>compare the results.
>
>I agree.  How viable would be just a CRC of a secret key?  It would be very
>easy to implement.  Would this be sufficient if the key was well chosen?  Maybe
>write a crc that forms 16 byte output?

I'm afraid I'm misunderstanding your point; it seems to me that you want 
to transmit a CRC (or a cryptographic hash value which comes in lengths 
of 16 or 20 bytes when you use MD5 or SHA, respectively) *instead* of a
secret key?? In this case the checksum simply acts *as* a secret key but 
is transmitted in clear. Thus you wouldn't need the secret key in the 
first place, and the whole procedure is not very secure because the same 
"secret" string is always transmitted in the same form. 

Sorry if I misinterpret your article; if so, please elaborate a bit more. 

A final remark on the original problem: As the laptop is _not_ regarded 
secure, an asymmetric algorithm would indeed be the right choice. It should 
be used for encryption [of a conventional key] _and_ signature so that the 
person schlepping the laptop can neither read and misuse the data nor 
make illegal modifications to it. Basically you have to reinvent something 
like PGP or RIPEM -- or just use one of these if you get all the legal and 
financial problems settled ...

